``Tsuno Shrine'' is located in {{ill|lt=Miyazaki Prefecture|Q130300|WD=Q130300|1=Miyazaki Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Koyu District|Q1132169|WD=Q1132169|1=Koyu District, Miyazaki}}{{ill|lt=Tsuno Town|Q1205974|WD=Q1205974|1=Tsuno, Miyazaki}}. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, {{ill|lt=Hyuga Country|Q513737|WD=Q513737|1=Hyūga Province}}{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}}. {{ill|lt=Modern Shrine Ranking System|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old Shrine Ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=Modern Shrine Ranking System|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old Shrine|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=Modern Shrine Ranking System#Government Shrine|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Kokuhei-kosha|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, and currently it is {{ill|lt=Beppedo Shrine|Q10898274|WD=Q10898274|1=Beppyo shrine}} of {{ill|lt=Shinto Honcho|Q908077|WD=Q908077|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}}.

Before {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, it was also called ``Miyazaki-sha'' and ``Miyazaki-miya''. It is also called ``Ichinomiya Shrine'' locally.

=== Enshrined God ===
* '''{{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōmi Takamikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}''' (Onamuchi Mikoto)
*: Same as Okuninushi no Mikoto. Since it has been the guardian deity of the Tsuno-cho area since ancient times, it is said that it was dedicated to the deity of the land.

Furthermore, ``{{ill|lt=Kinbukuro|Q17213633|WD=Q17213633|1=Chiribukuro}}'' has the text ``Tsu no Daimyojin.''<ref>There is a theory that this article in ``Kinbukuro'' is an anecdote from ``{{ill|lt=Fudōki|Q1194534|WD=Q1194534|lt=Hyuga Province Fudoki|1=Fudoki}},'' but this is being questioned (Iwanami Japanese Classical Literature Compendium ``Fudōki''). </ref>, ``{{ill|lt=Jinzoe壒壒鈔|Q30928164|WD=Q30928164|1=Jinten Ainōshō}}'' adds an additional note to it and states that it is a miraculous cure for {{ill|lt=smallpox|Q12214|WD=Q12214|lt=smallpox|1=Smallpox}}. It was also believed that it would remove insect damage from the fields.

=== History ===

=== Founding ===
According to the shrine's legend, {{ill|lt=Emperor Jinmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}} began worshiping the shrine six years before his ascension to the throne, when the Emperor was en route to the {{ill|lt=Jinmu Tosei|Q11590444|WD=Q11590444|lt=Eastern Conquest|1=Jimmu's Eastern Expedition}}. </ref>. In addition, an article in ``Jinzoe Ibukuro'' that says that {{ill|lt=Empress Jingu|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}} solicited ``Tuno Daimyojin'' as a guardian deity for boats during the {{ill|lt=Sanhan Conquest|Q11249435|WD=Q11249435|1=Three Han Campaign}} <ref>This article is already in ``Jinbukuro'' and, as mentioned in the previous note, is regarded as an anecdote from ``Fudoki''. Citing </ref>, it is reported that the shrine was first built by the Empress after her triumphant return. Similarly, in ``{{ill|lt=Jinbukuro|Q17213633|WD=Q17213633|1=Chiribukuro}}'', when Empress Jingu returned from the Sanhan Conquest, when she shot a bow at ``Bama-no-mine'', a black head appeared out of the soil, so she dug it up in the mountain, and two people, a man and a woman, appeared, and she summoned them as {{ill|lt=jinjin|Q11588676|WD=Q11588676|1=Jinin}}.

In addition to ruins dating back to the {{ill|lt=Jomon period|Q52824|WD=Q52824|1=Jōmon period}}, there are more than 20 ancient tombs (Tsuno kofun group) such as {{ill|lt=circular tumulus|Q11394747|WD=Q11394747|1=Round Kofun}} and {{ill|lt=keyhole-shaped tumulus|Q11268718|WD=Q11268718|1=Zenpō-kōen-fun}}, and pottery and stone tools have been excavated near our company's shrine. It is known that people lived there from an early time, and the history of our company as a guardian deity dates back to ancient times.

=== Outline ===
{{ill|lt=Jowa (Japan)|Q1075605|WD=Q1075605|lt=Jowa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}} In the 4th year ({{ill|lt=837|Q25093|WD=Q25093|1=837}}), he was promoted to a government shrine, and in the 10th year of Jowa ({{ill|lt=843|Q23469|WD=Q23469|1=843}}), he was given the rank of Junior Fifth Rank (hereinafter referred to as ``{{ill|lt=Shoku Nippon Ki|Q1041301|WD=Q1041301|1=Shoku Nihon Kōki}}''), {{ill|lt=Tenan (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} In 2nd year ({{ill|lt=858|Q30371|WD=Q30371|1=858}}), he was promoted to Jushii (Junior Fourth Rank) ("{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}"). In "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, ``'''Tsuno Shrine'''' is written in {{ill|lt=Hyuga Province|Q513737|WD=Q513737|1=Hyūga Province}}{{ill|lt=Koyu District|Q1132169|WD=Q1132169|1=Koyu District, Miyazaki}}, and it is listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinouchi Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}. It is said that at that time it was the largest shrine in Hyuga Province, with a magnificent shrine building and vast grounds. It is said that this position caused a political and religious conflict with {{ill|lt=Tsuman Shrine|Q3541658|WD=Q3541658|1=Tsuma Shrine}}, which is listed in <ref name="Gods">Tsunō Shrine in ``Japanese Gods''. </ref>As will be explained later, the details are not clear because the ancient documents were destroyed.It is certain that our company was revered not only by the common people but also by the local feudal lords as ``Ichinomiya of Hyuga Province'', and in {{ill|lt=Tenbun (era name)|Q1192853|WD=Q1192853|lt=Tenbun|1=Tenbun}}18 ({{ill|lt=1549|Q6554|WD=Q6554|1=1549}}), the shrine building was rebuilt by {{ill|lt=Yoshisuke Ito|Q6095349|WD=Q6095349|1=Itō Yoshisuke}}. Later, in {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}}6 ({{ill|lt=1578|Q6707|WD=Q6707|1=1578}}), during the conflict between the Otomo and Shimazu armies, {{ill|lt=Otomoyoshi It gradually declined after the shrine building, shrine treasures, and ancient documents were all destroyed in the fires of Chin|Q1185032|WD=Q1185032|lt=Otomo Sorin|1=Ōtomo Sōrin}} and {{ill|lt=Yoshihisa Shimazu|Q955727|WD=Q955727|1=Shimazu Yoshihisa}}. In {{ill|lt=Enpo|Q1145735|WD=Q1145735|1=Enpō}} 3rd year ({{ill|lt=1675|Q7624|WD=Q7624|1=1675}}), ``After that, there was no one to collect it, and it became a small shrine, unknown to the name, and only worshiped as a deity.'' </ref>The situation was as follows.After that, it was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 5th year ({{ill|lt=1692|Q7685|WD=Q7685|1=1692}}) by {{ill|lt=Takanabe clan|Q3034541|WD=Q3034541|lt=Takanabe clan lord|1=Takanabe Domain}} {{ill|lt=Akizuki Tanemasa|Q11595121|WD=Q11595121|1=Akizuki Tanemasa}} Since 20 koku of shrine territory was donated in the 14th year of Genroku ({{ill|lt=1701|Q6814|WD=Q6814|1=1701}}), it has been revered by successive {{ill|lt=Takanabe clan|Q3034541|WD=Q3034541|lt=Takanabe feudal lord|1=Takanabe Domain}} throughout the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}. Torii dedicated by {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} in 12 years ({{ill|lt=1727|Q6942|WD=Q6942|1=1727}}) by {{ill|lt=Tanehiro Akizuki|Q11595118|WD=Q11595118|1=Akizuki Tanehiro}}. The construction of the shrine in {{ill|lt=1736|Q6989|WD=Q6989|1=1736}} by {{ill|lt=Tanemi Akizuki|Q11595125|WD=Q11595125|1=Tanemi Akizuki}} and {{ jalink|Enkyo|Q1183728}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=1745|Q7586|WD=Q7586|1=1745}}) Torii gate construction, {{ill|lt=Ansei|Q1327259|WD=Q1327259|1=Ansei}}6th year ({{ill|lt=Ansei|Q1327259|WD=Q1327259|1=Ansei}}) k|1859|Q7687}})'s {{ill|lt=Akizuki Tanekin|Q11595126|WD=Q11595126|lt=Dosokuin|1=Akizuki Tanetomi}}, the shrine building was constructed, and the lords of the domain often visited the shrine, made deputations, and offered offerings.{{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}4 ({{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|WD=Q7746|1=1871}}) In {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}{{ill|lt=Modern company rank system#government company|Q7 12534|WD=Q7 12534|lt=Kokuhei-kosha}}, and in {{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}9 ({{ill|lt=1934|Q18714|WD=Q18714|1=1934}}), the area of the shrine was expanded and improved as part of the ``2600th Anniversary of Emperor Jimmu's Transfer to the East.'' After the war, it belonged to {{ill|lt=Shrine Honcho|Q908077|WD=Q908077|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}}, and in 1948 ({{ill|lt=1948|Q5165|WD=Q5165|1=1948}}) It became Omote Shrine|Q10898274}}, and the main shrine was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}}19 ({{ill|lt=2007|Q2024|WD=Q2024|1=2007}}).

=== God level ===
* In August of {{ill|lt=Jowa (Japan)|Q1075605|WD=Q1075605|lt=Jowa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}} 4th year ({{ill|lt=837|Q25093|WD=Q25093|1=837}}), it was promoted to a government shrine (``{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihon Koki|Q1041301|WD=Q1041301|1=Shoku Nihon Kōki}}'') - It is written as ``Shitonojin.''
*September 19, 10th year of Jowa ({{ill|lt=843|Q23469|WD=Q23469|1=843}}), from no rank to junior fifth rank ("Shoku Nihon Koki") - Written as "Tsuno Kojin".
* {{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} October 22, 2nd year ({{ill|lt=858|Q30371|WD=Q30371|1=858}}), from the upper fifth rank to the upper fourth rank (``{{ill|lt=Japan Three Dynasties Annals|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'')

=== Precincts ===
[[File:Tsuno-jinja honden.JPG|thumb|200px|right|main hall]]
The main shrine is {{ill|lt=Nagaruzou|Q210684|WD=Q210684|lt=Ikkensha Nagaruzou|1=Nagare-zukuri}} with a copper plate roof and {{ill|lt=Chigi/Katsuoki|Q87220234|WD=Q87220234|1=chigi and katsuogi}}. It was rebuilt in 2007 and largely follows the shape of the old main shrine. The old main shrine was rebuilt in 1986 with a donation from Kinosuke Kono, and it has now been relocated and serves as the main shrine of Kumano Shrine, a subsidiary shrine.

The worship hall, like the main shrine, was rebuilt in 2007. It is a {{ill|lt=irimoya-zukuri|Q855025|WD=Q855025|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}} with 5 rooms in the front and 3 spaces on the sides, and a {{ill|lt=gable-zukuri|Q13308575|WD=Q13308575|1=Kirizuma-style}} tsumairi shrine with a depth of 2 ken in the center of the back. The roof is made of copper sheets, with a {{ill|lt=gable #form of gables|Q4881511|WD=Q4881511|lt=staggered gable|1=Bargeboard}} on the front, and below that is a three-room {{ill|lt=facing gable|Q11415970|WD=Q11415970|1=kōhai}} with a gable and a gable in the center. The old worship hall has been relocated and is now used as a kagura hall.

In ancient times, the Ichi-no-Torii gate was located near Tsuno High School ({{Coord|32|15|06.90|N|131|33|43.93|E|region:JP-45_type:landmark|name=Ichi-no-Torii ruins}}), and its size shows the power of the past.

